featured_reviews.review_translated_text: There is logic and beauty in every law and practice of Islam. There is no deed in Islam which is difficult for a Muslim to observe. There are five pillars in Islam - Kalama, Namaz, Roza, Hajj and Zakat. Among these five pillars, prayer and fasting are obligatory for everyone, rich and poor. However, Hajj and Zakat are compulsory only for the wealthy. In some cases, including physical illness, there is an order to break the obligatory fast and it can be made up later. After breaking the fast, a disabled person can make expiation for the fast by feeding a fakir, a poor person full of food - this is also a provision in Islam. However, the command to perform Qaza in the case of Namaz is given only in special cases and there is no expiation or replacement of Namaz. It has been said that if there is a danger that the prayer will not be performed due to lack of water, then he should perform tayammum and perform the prayer. If a person cannot pray standing, he should pray sitting. If someone finds it difficult to pray while sitting, he should pray lying down. It is even said to pray with eye gestures.
